{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOMAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOMAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
III. First Amendment Protections
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYMAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYMAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The primary argument FAIR asserted was straightforward: the Solomon Amendment violated its First Amendment rights. The three grounds for FAIR\rquote s assertion, delineated below, were rooted in the First Amendment\rquote s freedom of expression, freedom of association, and the doctrine of unconstitutional conditions.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EHNAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EHNAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. Freedom of Expression
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ERNAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ERNAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The First Amendment generally protects the right to freedom of expression from most government interference.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F28333572300_ID0EZNAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F28333572300_ID0EZNAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F28333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
28
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Freedom of expression consists of freedom of speech, press, and assembly; the right to petition the government for redress of grievances; and, finally, the implied rights of association and belief.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F29333572300_ID0E5NAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F29333572300_ID0E5NAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F29333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
29
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The most basic component of freedom of expression is freedom of speech, which allows individuals to express themselves without interference or constraint by the government.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F30333572300_ID0EDOAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F30333572300_ID0EDOAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F30333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
30
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Constitution requires the government to provide substantial justification for curtailing free speech rights where it attempts to regulate the content of the speech.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F31333572300_ID0EIOAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F31333572300_ID0EIOAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F31333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
31
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A less stringent test is applied for content-neutral legislation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F32333572300_ID0ENOAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F32333572300_ID0ENOAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F32333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
32
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Supreme Court has also recognized that the government may prohibit some speech that may cause a breach of peace or cause violence.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F33333572300_ID0EROAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F33333572300_ID0EROAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F33333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
33
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYOAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYOAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Freedom of Association
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ECPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ECPAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Although the freedom of association has for the most part grown out of the protections of the First Amendment\rquote s guarantees of speech, assembly, 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_79_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_79_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*79
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and petition,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F34333572300_ID0ENPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F34333572300_ID0ENPAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F34333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
34
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 it has occasionally been referred to as if it were a separate, independent freedom within the First Amendment.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F35333572300_ID0ESPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F35333572300_ID0ESPAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F35333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
35
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Regardless, the freedom of association has become entrenched in American jurisprudence as a fundamental protection afforded under the Constitution.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F36333572300_ID0EWPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F36333572300_ID0EWPAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F36333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
36
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4PAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4PAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The lineage of cases addressing freedom of association is fairly recent, having arisen primarily in the 1950s and 1960s after the creation of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (hereinafter \u8220\'3fNAACP\u8221\'3f). In NAACP v. Alabama ex rel. Patterson, the Court unanimously set aside a contempt citation imposed after the organization refused to comply with a court order to produce a list of its members within the state.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F37333572300_ID0EIQAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F37333572300_ID0EIQAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F37333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
37
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In ruling in favor of the NAACP\rquote s privacy of its membership, the Court held that \u8220\'3f[e]ffective advocacy of both public and private points of view, particularly controversial ones, is undeniably enhanced by group association, as this Court has more than once recognized by remarking upon the close nexus between the freedoms of speech and assembly.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F38333572300_ID0EVQAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F38333572300_ID0EVQAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F38333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
38
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E3QAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E3QAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In a series of three decisions, the Court explored the extent to which associational rights may be burdened by nondiscrimination requirements. First, Roberts v. United States Jaycees held that the Minnesota Human Rights Act prohibited the United States Jaycees from excluding women from full membership.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F39333572300_ID0EHRAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F39333572300_ID0EHRAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F39333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
39
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Three years later, in Board of Directors of Rotary International v. Rotary Club of Duarte,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F40333572300_ID0EKRAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F40333572300_ID0EKRAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F40333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
40
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the Court applied Roberts in upholding a similar California law to prevent Rotary International from excluding women from membership.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F41333572300_ID0EPRAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F41333572300_ID0EPRAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F41333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
41
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Finally, in New York State Club 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_80_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_80_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*80
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Ass\rquote n v. New York City,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F42333572300_ID0EXRAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F42333572300_ID0EXRAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F42333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
42
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the Court upheld, against facial challenge, New York City\rquote s Human Rights Law, which prohibited race, creed, sex, and other discrimination in places \u8220\'3fof public accommodation, resort or amusement.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F43333572300_ID0EESAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F43333572300_ID0EESAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F43333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
43
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ELSAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ELSAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In each case, private organizations sought to retain their organizational rights to associate only with certain types, creed, races, or genders of people.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F44333572300_ID0ETSAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F44333572300_ID0ETSAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F44333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
44
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In the Court\rquote s view, however, their associational rights were not as important as the government\rquote s compelling interest to control with whom such organizations may lawfully associate.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F45333572300_ID0EYSAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F45333572300_ID0EYSAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F45333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
45
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Despite these rulings, however, some amount of First Amendment protection is still granted to such organizations; the Jaycees and its members, for example, have taken public positions on a number of issues and engaged in \u8220\'3fa variety of civic, charitable, lobbying, fundraising, and other activities worthy of constitutional protection.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F46333572300_ID0EGTAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F46333572300_ID0EGTAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F46333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
46
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, the Roberts Court found \u8220\'3fno basis in the record for concluding that admission of women as full voting members will impede the organization\rquote s ability to engage in these protected activities or to disseminate its preferred views.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F47333572300_ID0EUTAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F47333572300_ID0EUTAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F47333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
47
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Moreover, the state had a \u8220\'3fcompelling interest to prevent acts of invidious discrimination in the distribution of publicly available goods, services, and other advantages.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F48333572300_ID0EBUAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F48333572300_ID0EBUAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F48333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
48
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EIUAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EIUAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Jaycees and Rotary Clubs were, by their very nature of service and availability, almost akin to public clubs. The Court in Roberts likened the situation to a large corporation attempting to discriminate in hiring or selecting customers.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F49333572300_ID0ETUAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F49333572300_ID0ETUAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F49333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
49
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 These cases, thus, are exceptional and probably should not be interpreted as having broad application in light of the low number of equivalently-sized national service organizations.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E3UAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E3UAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
On the other hand, when application of a public accommodations law was viewed as impinging on an organization\rquote s ability to present its message, the Court found a First Amendment violation. For example, in Hurley v. Irish-American Gay Group,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F50333572300_ID0EFVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F50333572300_ID0EFVAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F50333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
50
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the State of Massachusetts could not require the private organizers of Boston\rquote s St. Patrick\rquote s Day parade to allow a group of gays and lesbians to march as a unit proclaiming its members\rquote  
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_81_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_81_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*81
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 gay and lesbian identity. To do so, reasoned the court, would require parade organizers to promote a message they did not wish to promote.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F51333572300_ID0ESVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F51333572300_ID0ESVAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F51333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
51
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Hurley court distinguished the Roberts and New York City cases as not involving a \u8220\'3ftrespass on the organization\rquote s message itself.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F52333572300_ID0EAWAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F52333572300_ID0EAWAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F52333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
52
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Rather, those cases stood for the proposition that the state could require equal access for individuals to what was considered the public benefit of organization membership.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F53333572300_ID0EFWAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F53333572300_ID0EFWAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F53333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
53
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Even if individual access to the parade might similarly be mandated, however, the Court reasoned the gay group \u8220\'3fcould nonetheless be refused admission as an expressive contingent with its own message just as readily as a private club could exclude an applicant whose manifest views were at odds with a position taken by the club\rquote s existing members.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F54333572300_ID0ESWAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F54333572300_ID0ESWAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F54333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
54
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EZWAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EZWAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The significant part of the right of association exists in the area of political associational rights; the freedom to associate with others who share the same political beliefs, for example, has been recognized by the Supreme Court as a practice protected by the First Amendment.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F55333572300_ID0EBXAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F55333572300_ID0EBXAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F55333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
55
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Consequently, laws attempting to force associations to accept beliefs or accommodate views they find repugnant, as FAIR contended, would be scrutinized closely.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F56333572300_ID0EFXAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F56333572300_ID0EFXAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F56333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
56
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMXAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMXAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Unconstitutional Conditions Doctrine
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWXAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWXAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The doctrine of unconstitutional conditions essentially means that the Federal Government may not require an individual to surrender a constitutional right as a condition of receiving some government-provided benefit such as employment, medical care, grant of money, right, privilege, or other benefit.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F57333572300_ID0E5XAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F57333572300_ID0E5XAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F57333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
57
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The government, in other words, may not seek waivers of constitutional rights through conditioned benefits because those rights are not properly the subject of barter.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F58333572300_ID0EDYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F58333572300_ID0EDYAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F58333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
58
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Government should not, as Justice Douglas states, \u8220\'3fbuy up\u8221\'3f the constitutional rights of its citizens.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F59333572300_ID0EHYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F59333572300_ID0EHYAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F59333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
59
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOYAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_82_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_82_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*82
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The 1958 case of Speiser v. Randall
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F60333572300_ID0EYYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F60333572300_ID0EYYAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F60333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
60
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 comprised one of the first modern era interpretations of unconstitutional conditions doctrine.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F61333572300_ID0E4YAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F61333572300_ID0E4YAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F61333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
61
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Speiser involved a California property tax exemption for World War II veterans who declared under oath that they would not overthrow the Government of the United States or the State of California, nor advocate the support of a foreign Government against the United States in the event of hostilities.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F62333572300_ID0ECZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F62333572300_ID0ECZAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F62333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
62
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Supreme Court held that California could not require a waiver of a constitutional right as a condition of receiving a tax benefit.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F63333572300_ID0EHZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F63333572300_ID0EHZAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F63333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
63
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although California argued that the oath merely restated a forbearance from committing what was already a crime\u8212\'3fthe overthrow of the government by force or violence\u8212\'3fthe Court rejected the state\rquote s reasoning. While the state alone has the burden of proving guilt of a crime, California attempted to require citizens to swear that they were not engaging in prohibited speech, making the individuals, should they be investigated later, presumptively guilty of a crime.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F64333572300_ID0EOZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F64333572300_ID0EOZAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F64333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
64
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EVZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EVZAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Another seminal unconstitutional conditions case is a 1963 case dealing with the availability of unemployment benefits provided by South Carolina.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F65333572300_ID0E4ZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F65333572300_ID0E4ZAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F65333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
65
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The claimant, a Seventh-Day Adventist, was discharged by her employer for refusing to work on Saturday, the Sabbath Day of her faith. She applied for and was denied unemployment compensation from the South Carolina Employment Commission because she refused to work on Saturdays, which barred her from employment for failure to accept suitable work.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F66333572300_ID0EF1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F66333572300_ID0EF1AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F66333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
66
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Supreme Court held that the government imposition of a choice between benefits and her religion put the same kind of burden upon the free exercise of religion as would a fine imposed against the appellant for her Saturday worship.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F67333572300_ID0EJ1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F67333572300_ID0EJ1AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F67333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
67
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EQ1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EQ1AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Despite the quantity of case law demonstrating that an individual cannot forego a right in order to secure a privilege from the government, numerous other cases have been decided to the contrary. Such cases have 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_83_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_83_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*83
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 involved, inter alia, the requirement that laborers join a union as a condition of being employed;
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F68333572300_ID0E51AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F68333572300_ID0E51AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F68333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
68
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the permitting of a defendant to waive his constitutional right to a trial by jury, as codified in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1004365&cite=USFRCRPR23&originatingDoc=I456def107cf011dca51ecfdfa1ed2cd3&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Federal Rule of Criminal Procedure 23(a)
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F69333572300_ID0EJ2AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F69333572300_ID0EJ2AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F69333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
69
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 or his right to a trial but instead opt for a plea bargain;
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F70333572300_ID0EM2AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F70333572300_ID0EM2AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F70333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
70
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and the requirement that attorneys join a state bar association as a condition of being granted a license to practice law in that state.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F71333572300_ID0ER2AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F71333572300_ID0ER2AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F71333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
71
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Not coincidentally, the above-referenced decisions by the Supreme Court never mention the unconstitutional conditions doctrine or why it would not apply to these cases. The unconstitutional conditions doctrine and its progeny of case law is neither clearly defined, nor well articulated, in existing decisions.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E42AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E42AE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
IV. The Court\rquote s Ruling in Rumsfeld v. FAIR
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EH3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EH3AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Chief Justice Roberts wrote the unanimous Court decision,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F72333572300_ID0EN3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F72333572300_ID0EN3AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F72333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
72
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 which held that the Solomon Amendment did not violate the objecting law schools\rquote  freedoms of speech and association under the First Amendment.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F73333572300_ID0ES3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F73333572300_ID0ES3AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F73333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
73
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The opinion focused on interpreting the Solomon Amendment; Congress\rquote  power to raise and support a military; Congress\rquote  power of the purse; and First Amendment implications.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F74333572300_ID0EW3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F74333572300_ID0EW3AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F74333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
74
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E43AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E43AE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. The Meaning and Interpretation of the Solomon Amendment
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EH4AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EH4AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
At the outset, the Court discussed the meaning of the Solomon Amendment.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F75333572300_ID0EQ4AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F75333572300_ID0EQ4AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F75333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
75
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although both FAIR and the federal government agreed on what the Solomon Amendment required\u8212\'3fthat if a law school and its university want to receive federal funding, the law school must offer military recruiters the same access to its campus and students that it provides to the nonmilitary recruiter
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F76333572300_ID0ET4AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F76333572300_ID0ET4AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F76333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
76
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u8212\'3famici briefs submitted by certain law professors disagreed.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F77333572300_ID0EY4AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F77333572300_ID0EY4AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F77333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
77
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 According to these amici, the Solomon Amendment\rquote s equal-access requirement is satisfied when a college applies to military recruiters 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_84_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_84_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*84
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the same policy it applies to all other recruiters.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F78333572300_ID0EC5AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F78333572300_ID0EC5AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F78333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
78
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Using this logic, a university excluding military recruiters would be in compliance with the Solomon Amendment so long as it also excluded any other employer that violates its nondiscrimination policy.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F79333572300_ID0EG5AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F79333572300_ID0EG5AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F79333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
79
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EN5AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EN5AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Court quickly dismissed this interpretation of the Solomon Amendment, stating that the Act requires the same degree of access to students on campuses that is provided to any other employer.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F80333572300_ID0EV5AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F80333572300_ID0EV5AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F80333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
80
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court noted that, under amici\rquote s reading, a military recruiter has the same \u8220\'3faccess\u8221\'3f to campuses and students as any other private law firm when the law firm is permitted on campus to interview the students when the military is not.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F81333572300_ID0E15AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F81333572300_ID0E15AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F81333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
81
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court did not believe that the military recruiter would have received equal \u8220\'3faccess\u8221\'3f in that type of situation, regardless of the fact that the unequal treatment is due to the military\rquote s failure to comply with the schools\rquote  nondiscrimination policies.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F82333572300_ID0E65AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F82333572300_ID0E65AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F82333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
82
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EG6AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EG6AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Having decided what the Solomon Amendment required of the law schools, the Court then focused on whether Congress had the power to enact such legislation. There were two possible bases for Congress\rquote  power to enact this law: the power of Congress to raise and support the military
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F83333572300_ID0EP6AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F83333572300_ID0EP6AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F83333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
83
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and its power to tax and spend.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F84333572300_ID0EU6AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F84333572300_ID0EU6AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F84333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
84
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court addressed each in turn.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E46AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E46AE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Congress\rquote  Power to Raise and Support Armies
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EIAAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EIAAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Under the Constitution, Congress is granted the power to \u8220\'3f[p]rovide for the common Defence,\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F85333572300_ID0EXAAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F85333572300_ID0EXAAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F85333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
85
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 to raise and support armies, and to provide and maintain a navy\u8212\'3fin short, to create the military.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F86333572300_ID0E3AAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F86333572300_ID0E3AAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F86333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
86
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court, citing one of its prior decisions, noted that Congress\rquote  power in this area is \u8220\'3fbroad and sweeping.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F87333572300_ID0EBBAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F87333572300_ID0EBBAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F87333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
87
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 It further noted that there was \u8220\'3fno dispute in this case that it includes the authority to require campus access for military recruiters,\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F88333572300_ID0ENBAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F88333572300_ID0ENBAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F88333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
88
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 so long as it does not overstep constitutional limitations.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F89333572300_ID0ESBAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F89333572300_ID0ESBAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F89333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
89
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court indicated that it would give the highest degree of deference when it came to Congress\rquote  power to legislate under its authority to raise 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100319_85_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100319_85_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*85
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and support armies.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F90333572300_ID0E3BAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F90333572300_ID0E3BAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F90333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
90
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Therefore, the Court found that Congress could have enacted the Solomon Amendment using this power, even though Congress chose to employ a different basis for its enactment. The Court then turned its attention to the actual basis for Congressional enactment of the Solomon Amendment: the power to tax and spend.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EICAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EICAG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Congressional Spending Clause Powers
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ESCAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ESCAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Despite the fact that Congress could have simply required schools to accommodate military recruiters under its power to raise and support a military, it chose a different means: its spending clause power, also referred to as the power of the purse.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F91333572300_ID0E1CAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F91333572300_ID0E1CAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F91333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
91
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 By using its spending clause authority, Congress attempted to leverage universities by giving them a choice either to allow military recruiters the same access to students afforded any other recruiter or forego certain federal funds.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F92333572300_ID0E6CAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F92333572300_ID0E6CAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F92333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
92
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court noted that the federal government is \u8220\'3ffree to attach reasonable and unambiguous conditions to federal financial assistance that educational institutions are not obligated to accept.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F93333572300_ID0EMDAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F93333572300_ID0EMDAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F93333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
93
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ETDAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ETDAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Congress\rquote  power to place conditions upon the receipt of funds, however, is not unlimited.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F94333572300_ID0E2DAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F94333572300_ID0E2DAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F94333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
94
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court noted instances where the government could not deny benefits to a person on a basis that infringes upon constitutionally protected freedoms of speech.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F95333572300_ID0EAEAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F95333572300_ID0EAEAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F95333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
95
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 This principle of unconstitutional conditions was inapplicable here, the Court reasoned, because it cannot apply to situations where Congress could have imposed the requirement directly.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F96333572300_ID0EGEAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F96333572300_ID0EGEAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F96333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
96
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In other words, since Congress could have required schools to admit military recruiters using its power to raise a military, it could also do so by using the spending clause without running afoul of the unconstitutional conditions doctrine.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F97333572300_ID0EKEAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F97333572300_ID0EKEAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F97333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
97
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EREAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EREAG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
