{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
 D. The Solomon Amendment and the First Amendment\rquote s Freedom of Speech
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6EAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6EAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Although the Court ruled that Congress technically had the power to enact the Solomon Amendment, FAIR still asserted that the Act unconstitutionally infringed upon schools\rquote  First Amendment freedom of speech on three separate grounds. First, FAIR claimed that the Solomon Amendment forced the schools to assist military recruiters by sending email announcements and distributing flyers that clearly involved speech.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F98333572300_ID0EKFAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F98333572300_ID0EKFAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F98333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
98
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 FAIR asserted that, in supplying these services, law schools were unconstitutionally compelled to speak the government\rquote s message.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F99333572300_ID0EPFAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F99333572300_ID0EPFAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F99333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
99
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Second, FAIR noted that because military recruiters are speaking while on campus, the Solomon Amendment, by forcing law schools to permit the military on campus to express its message, unconstitutionally required law schools to host or accommodate the military\rquote s speech.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F100333572300_ID0EUFAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F100333572300_ID0EUFAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F100333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
100
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Third, FAIR asserted that the Solomon Amendment also regulated expressive conduct in violation of the Constitution; specifically, it forced the law schools to stop expressing their objection to the military\rquote s homosexual policy.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F101333572300_ID0EZFAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F101333572300_ID0EZFAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F101333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
101
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Finally, FAIR argued that even if the Solomon Amendment did not violate its First Amendment freedom of speech, it infringed upon its freedom of association by preventing the schools from only associating with those that share its nondiscrimination views.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F102333572300_ID0E5FAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F102333572300_ID0E5FAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F102333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
102
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court considered each argument in turn.
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
