105
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Solomon Amendment, unlike prior cases, did not dictate the content of the speech; the minor abridgement in this case was merely an incidental regulation of conduct.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F106333572300_ID0EQHAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F106333572300_ID0EQHAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F106333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
106
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court held that simply because the conduct was in part initiated or carried out by means of language\u8212\'3feither spoken, written, or printed\u8212\'3fthis alone does not infringe upon speech.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F107333572300_ID0EVHAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F107333572300_ID0EVHAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F107333572300_1" }{\fldrslt 
