{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
However, if FAIR\rquote s original purpose was to attack the military\rquote s policy towards openly homosexual members, why did they create a three-year long diversion from that goal\u8212\'3fduring wartime, costing law schools and government hundreds of thousands of dollars to litigate\u8212\'3fjust to point out frivolous infringements of First Amendment rights? Although it may be too glib to say that the professors were simply subpar advocates, perhaps they were emboldened by the belief that there was no difference between law and politics. In that sense, they believed they would have automatically secured the more left-leaning justices with their self-proclaimed progressive cause, despite its unfounded support under constitutional scrutiny. It is also very likely that, despite realizing the weakness of their case, FAIR and its supporters saw an opportunity for immediate media attention for their symbolic expression of a gay rights agenda.
