The first iteration denied any funds from the Department of Defense (hereinafter \u8220\'3fDOD\u8221\'3f) to schools that barred military recruiters from campus. However, the denial of such funds did not apply to the entire institution; instead, the denial was limited to the particular school that denied entry to military recruiters. In 1997, Congress extended the law\rquote s reach to include funds from the Departments of Education, Labor, and Health & Human Services. In 1999, the Frank-Campbell Amendment removed funds from the federal monies potentially affected by the Solomon Amendment. In 2000, the DOD toughened the law by expanding its effect to the entire institution. In other words, even if only one of an institution\rquote s subdivisions, such as its law school, ran afoul of the legal requirements regarding allowing military recruiters on campus, DOD funds granted to the entire institution would be revoked. Forum for Academic Institutional Rights, 
