. In Roberts, both the Jaycees\rquote  nearly indiscriminate membership requirements and the State\rquote s compelling interest in prohibiting discrimination against women were important to the Court\rquote s analysis. Id. at 621. The Court found, \u8220\'3fthe local chapters of the Jaycees are large and basically unselective groups,\u8221\'3f age and sex being the only established membership criteria in organizations otherwise entirely open to public participation. Id. The Jaycees, therefore, \u8220\'3flack the distinctive characteristics [e.g., small size, identifiable purpose, selectivity in membership, perhaps seclusion from the public eye] that might afford constitutional protection to the decision of its members to exclude women.\u8221\'3f Id.
